VThis movie was so bad I kept on checking what time it was. The story was abysmal and the 3D didn't add much to it, it only made it worse. At the end of the movie I wished I watched the 2D version or didn't watch it at all. I really respect all the special effects and the CGI but the LOTR/Hobbit team has proved their CGI skills a million times and I think it should be about time for them to make one step further. A step towards good story, for instance. \u000a\u000aNot even trying to compare the mediocre Hobbit to the great Lord of the rings, I usually like these movies because they are versatile, the story is deep, there seems to be a certain atmosphere around them and there's values that the movies try to portray, there's usually a message it wants to give to you; here there was none of that. The one sub-plot that I got into got totally disfigured by the amount of time it spent off the storyline and by the violently cut ending. \u000a\u000aThe story got totally overwhelmed by the action, and I really felt like I could get action elsewhere. It just felt like the movie didn't have an edge, didn't try to bring anything new to the table, just stick with the same old formula and adding a pointless 3D, trying to make up for the story... the characters were lifeless, and very sadly, in 3D, the world was lifeless too. The thing that happens with 3D is that it isn't evolved enough and it cannot substitute a good 2D cinematography, because in 2D cinematography we can see different composition, colors, angles, while 3D brings messy (too dark!) colors, all-over the place angles and no composition can be seen whatsoever. I would much more appreciate the rich colors and the amazing world of 2D New Zealand.\u000a\u000aIt was just the kind of movie you could make a parody out of. Too many last-moment salvages from orcs, inconsistent action sequences, way too much talking (especially the self-glorification of the dragon) and way too much music... way too much of everything as a matter of fact.\u000a\u000aI think the novel got pummeled in the face of money, that was seen in people who will watch it out of habit. OK, obviously it had to be done, but they could have done it with more soul. And pretty ironically, I think money, greed and losing soul to darkness - kind of a mirror of our own world - are the main symbols of the LOTR and Hobbit series. And I hold a grudge to this movie because it didn't try to give anything new to the spectators (when we leave aside the expectedly thrilling world, which has been delivered so many times in this series), but a couple of good action sequences and a wannabe love-plot. It was all over the place. If I tried to make a summary, I couldn't. \u000a\u000aI liked Evangeline Lilly though.\u000a\u000aCall me critical, but 4/10
