VLet me first say that the movie would be a fine action film were it not Tolkien's work re-written by feminist hackneyed appeasers, and helmed by an egocentrist, who still hasn't gotten over the fan disapproval of his prior abortion, 'King Kong'.\u000a\u000aWhere to begin...\u000a\u000aI liked the film up until the spiders, but the relentless orc trackers are just overbearing, particularly their covert invasion of Laketown. And turning Laketown into some militaristic police state? Just childish. Did you really need to cast Stephen Fry and his right hand man as some comical bastardized imitation of Theoden and Wormtongue? Laketown was not a destitute slum.\u000a\u000aWomen have enjoyed a succession of strong female leads in many series and movies portraying them as action heroes over the last few decades: Zena Warrior Princess, Buffy the Vampire Slayer, Lost Girl's Bo, Lara Croft, Resident Evil's Alice, to name a few. Why did these hipster Hollywood writers feel Tolkien needed a woman's touch? If a male writer took Jane Austin's work and downplayed the female roles to place more emphasis on say, characters who weren't in her books at all, would these same writers think it a positive decision? The elf and dwarf romance angle actually made me ill. In love with a dwarf and Captain of the King's Guard? Please... \u000a\u000aI forgave Jackson his editing and lesser re-writes of the 'Lord of the Rings', because I did enjoy them despite the same screenwriters thumbing their noses at an actual author, in part because I waited many years for quality versions of the books. I can remember McCartney and Lennon wanted to star in a movie version back in the sixties - can you imagine? (Get it?)\u000a\u000aOne other aggravating path they took was turning Smaug into a gabby old washer woman. He is also connected to Sauron by his remarks, and is somehow aware of the power of the ring. These things never happened in the story. Smaug has very limited lines, but sees the situation clearly through his ancient cleverness, and is a power unto himself without any plans to join the Dark Lord, or share power. His limited dialog in the story was tightly written, and thereby more menacing. And that whole chase scene through Erebor was just irritating. If that kind of flame was that close, hiding behind a column would not save you. The fire would suck the air out of your lungs and set them on fire. How was Smaug so effective against the whole of Thrain's kingdom's army, but failed to kill even one member of the company?\u000a\u000aJackson has a way of visualizing most of Tolkien's world, but shouldn't have been involved in the writing, nor his chosen partners, as they failed to re-create what the man gave us in a classic tale. They did an injustice to his memory in their single minded need to make this epic story their own, rather than the man who authored it.\u000a\u000aI read many of these reviews, and it saddens me that our culture gives in to whatever Hollywood puts in front of them, rather than making some noise when we are presented with a lame copy of a wonderful story with plenty of adventure.
