VI went to see the 48 FPS / HFR version of this film. I generally arrive at the cinema 10 minutes or so after showtime, to minimize the adverts I need to sit through before the film. When I arrived on this occasion, though, I found the film had already started. I figured I couldn't have missed much, took a seat as quietly as possible, and began watching. It was clear, however, that the plot was already well-developed, and making reference to past events that I'd missed. I missed the first film in this trilogy when it was released last year, so I thought perhaps the gaps I was noticing were down to that. However, I quickly realised that even that couldn't account for the way the film felt as if it was in its third act. So, after watching for about ten minutes or so, I popped outside again to check I was in the correct showing. Sure enough, I had been in a showing of the 24 FPS version that had started about two hours earlier.\u000a\u000aI mention the above anecdote because when I eventually made my way into the right theatre and began watching the 'correct' 48 FPS version (from the beginning this time!), it was immediately apparent that it was a very different film to the one I had been watching in the room next door. I've read a bit since my viewing, and found that there was a lot of opinion in the blogosphere that reflects the reaction I had. So, anyone that's also read the general consensus of opinion that's out there from ordinary filmgoers like me can probably guess what's coming next.\u000a\u000aThe film looked, for want of a better word, cheap. It looked like it had been made for TV. The sets looked like sets. The CGI looked like CGI. Whenever there was an outside scene, it was readily apparent that there were two light sources in them, and one of them was artificial. The main leads looked like that guy from the British version of The Office and the one from Spooks, sporting obvious makeup and prosthetics, and wearing silly wigs. \u000a\u000aI'm not an out-and-out film geek, and I undoubtedly don't know as much about film-making as does Peter Jackson. But I am someone that loved The Hobbit as one of the first books I read as a child, and I am a huge fan of Jackson's original LOTR trilogy from 2001-2003. I'm also - bear with me here - a former psychology student and have a particular interest in the subject of hypnotism; it's always struck me how great film-making is one of the subtler forms of day-to-day hypnotism to which most people can relate. Film makers and fans talk about the so-called "suspension of disbelief" that's necessary for a great storyteller to tell an engaging story to an interested audience. It requires skill and willingness from each of the parties to the process for the magic to work. Part of the reason that I think the slower frame rate worked so well is that it allowed room for a willing audience's brains to fill in unseen details. Just like a dream feels realistic in the moment, but afterwards is clearly only a mere fuzzy representation of the experienced narrative, so too 24 FPS feels like a way of communicating the intent of the story whilst leaving subtler details to the imagination.\u000a\u000aBecause so little was left to the viewer's mind's eye, The Desolation of Smaug felt like watching a reasonable amateur dramatics production. But one where you'd made the mistake of sitting too close to the stage and could therefore see the men in black clothing moving the sets around, and could perceive that the 'snow' was really tissue paper. It felt a lot like watching a BBC TV production from the 1970s or early 1980s. Specifically, I Claudius and Doctor Who sprung to mind as being reminiscent of this experience. It's not that those earlier productions were bad for their era or genres, it's just that they're not *film*, and they're not what I was expecting to see from the latest in cinema technology in late 2013. \u000a\u000aIn terms of the CGI, this film reminded me of the type of CGI you used to get in 1990s cinema. Say, for example, in Terminator 2. Which at the time was the best we had, but looking back definitely feels a bit dated compared to the photo-realistic CGI that's common in non-HFR movies now. In HFR it's crystal-clear what is CGI and what is not, whilst in ordinary 24 FPS it can sometimes be hard to tell. (E.g., quick fact: the bullet holes in the police cars during the 'nun' bank heist scene in The Town were added subtly via CGI in post-production, which I didn't notice when watching the actual film, even though it makes sense given how close some of the pyrotechnics that might otherwise have been used would have needed to be to the stunt performers).\u000a\u000aIn short, HFR may be a good medium for showing actual reality. But at this point in time, it's not good for films involving fantasy elements that require prosthetics or makeup. And CGI has to make a further leap forward before it's good enough to be indistinguishable from (HFR) reality again.
