VI am not a Tolkien fan when I write this, I am just a casual viewer of the series because, well... I have almost no knowledge of the books except they were well respected and they kind of made the transition to having fantasy stories intended for adult audiences. Well, thought the original Lord Of The Rings trilogy was overrated but I still enjoyed them and they were above average and for The Hobbit: An Unexpected Journey. I kind of liked that but it's nothing on the originals... then there's this - the first one in all the series of which I didn't like.\u000a\u000aBilbo has continued his adventure as they draw nearer to the mountain in which the Dwarf kingdom that is rightfully theirs is. Bilbo must go in there and take back the stone in which will get the other dwarfs to join Thorin and the others to reign once again. But they all must face something together, a near-indestructible dragon by the name of Smaug.\u000a\u000aNow, before fans of this series jump all over me, I should say what I liked. Well as typical of the series, the acting is really good, The cinematography is a marvel to look at, the Art design is top of the line (well, maybe except on the Woodland Elf King... Sorry, I just couldn't take him seriously!) and the CG work in some cases out- rival the very best of the stuff today. Not to mention Smaug is definitely the best movie dragon I have seen so far.\u000a\u000aNow with something like that where does this movie fall short? The story. It might seem like I'm insulting Tolkien but I'm not. First of all, the love triangle is probably the most transparent way to drag in a female audience I've seen since Twilight, I have never read the book but even then it's so poorly woven into the story that you can tell from a mile off this isn't in there.\u000a\u000aThere are also some parts that are really stupid. I mean the first couple of minutes takes place in the Prancing Pony with Thorin and Gandalf... I don't know if they mention a time for when it takes place but the thoughts that would go through any nerd's mind (fan or not) is "wait a minute... shouldn't they be in the other direction and... a few hundred thousand miles away?" and they talk about the Orcs placing a price on Thorin's head... I repeat, in the middle of a PUBLIC BAR WHERE ANYONE CAN EAVESDROP they talk about the price on Thorin's head, shouldn't they think "What if someone in here's listening in and decides to kill Thorin and collect the money?", I know I'm nitpicking on this one scene but there is stuff like this all throughout the movie.\u000a\u000aThe very last thing I'll complain about (which it isn't a complaint on just this movie but more the entire Hobbit series) is that I know a couple of Tolkien readers and from what I've heard the book is about 300 pages long whereas this movie, combined with the first one is about 330 minutes plus another three hour movie coming out (which by my math makes it about 510 minutes). Now, the question is - How do you make a book adaptation where the book is shorter then the movies? It's a simple question.\u000a\u000aIf you want my personal opinion, the build-up for Smaug in the last movie was massive and here they really do have it pay off here. Aside from that the cinematography, art design and the acting are all worth watching this movie for. Aside from that, there are some things in the story that REALLY don't work. I mean if you like the original and want to see this movie then I guess there isn't that much harm in it. But for me personally, I'll watch The Hobbit 3 and that's as far as things'll go when it comes to me and this series.
