VLook, it gets 5 stars for being OK for what it is... it's just not the hobbit. \u000a\u000aI wanted to fall asleep during the last 15 mins, and I never do that in a film.\u000a\u000aI did like Gandalf facing the Necromancer in Dol Guldur, I did like some background bits, like him encouraging Thorin along in the inn at Bree. I did giggle when Bombur cut a swathe through the Orcs with the barrel, and then stuck his arms and legs out, but it could have easily done without. Or had that scene in some other way, eg, when they finally get out of the barrels. And where did the random spare barrel come from, as he jumps back in the water? Doesn't really matter, but...\u000a\u000aHowever, all the best bits have been left out. Again.\u000a\u000aIt has been destroyed... (oops, I mean adapted), for US cinema.\u000a\u000aGreat swathes of unnecessary complications, whilst taking out all the incidents that made the thing charming in the first place. Why is Fili wounded and left behind to be doctored by a meaningless elf maiden instead of going along? Why are any Dwarfs (I spelt dwarfs with a v...) left behind? Why all the 'song and dance' (figure of speech), with the Dragon chasing everyone about in the Mountain. It lost a lot of possible menace and atmosphere, there. Why a totally meaningless large gold statue of a dwarf that melts over Smaug. If it was trying to be a nod to the 'Alien' franchise, it missed completely. If it wasn't....????\u000a\u000aWhat happened to the sealed barrels? Bilbo nearly getting caught snitching the pie? The dwarf staggering out and saying he could eat anything for hours on end, but not an apple? Without these small touches, it loses so much. ''Thag you very buch''. \u000a\u000aAnd what's with the character assassinations?...again! Radagast was neither ridiculous, unintelligent, dirty nor cowardly as portrayed here. He was somewhat less worldly than the other wizards, and interested in animals. Think more along the lines of St Francis of Assisi, than dirty old tramp, like we got here. And why McCoy??? WHY??? So wrong. Unless you want a silly old duffer. Casting for random dingbat, yes. Casting for Wizard, no.\u000a\u000aThranduil wasn't quite as bad as all that, he just did what he saw fit to do and didn't enquire as far into it as he ought to have. He behaved rightly by his lights, and given the history between the wood elves and the dwarfs. Another character made worse.\u000a\u000aBard isn't quite as he's made to look here, either. And why is Bard's Black Arrow changed into the equivalent of a dragon lance? Why? For what purpose? It lends no excitement or interest to the story whatsoever. It's far MORE exciting to have one small man and his bow against a dragon than that giant bow-come-lance thrower contraption. Girion of Dale...More CA comin' your way, I say comin' your way!\u000a\u000aBeorn...looked like a man when in man shape...hairy - yes, yeti - no. And what happened to the introductions? And how Beorn was very pleased with them for killing the great goblin? (And thank heaven the goblins and orcs were more serious, and less like a vaudeville act crossed with comedy capers, as they were last time).\u000a\u000aBut seeing as we're at the lowest level possible, let's remain there. I was hoping I'd seen the last of 'racing sled-bunnies'. Yet here we are again, *sigh*. The 'buskies', as we call them at home, would be eaten by a random marauding Orc as soon as possible, if I had anything to do with it. \u000a\u000aLook it's absolutely fine if you've never read the books, a cheesy kiddy film, great.\u000a\u000aIt's just had the guts kicked out of what it was, for all the people that know and love the story. And it's SUCH a waste of talent and resources. The acting was really great, so where was the screenplay and story to match? Benedict Cumberbatch does a great job with the voices.\u000a\u000aI liked the LOTR trilogy, though I was really getting the poohs with it by the last one. This, I haven't liked much from the get go. It is a nice film, just not for me. I don't understand why you have to make up all this trash, when there is plenty of time-filler available in the book. I don't object to changing things at all - you have to for cinema, but this Hobbit thing has changed all the wrong things in all the wrong places so far as I can see. 'Lowest common denominator' language changes, useless story changes that distract rather than contribute. \u000a\u000aI wanted to see them have to carry the sleeping Bombur through the forest a bit. I did want to see the silly introduction to Beorn. I did want to see Bilbo teasing the spiders. I did want to see Bilbo trying to find enough straw to pack the Dwarfs in tightly. I did want to see a feast at Lake town where Bilbo has to make a speech while he's got a cold from being in the water so long, as he couldn't make shift to stay atop a barrel. I did want to see the intelligent birds at the Mountain... Roac son of Carc. I did want to see the dwarfs stumbling around disrupting the elvish revelries in the forest. \u000a\u000aDidn't.\u000a\u000aI gave it a go, and saw it, as people said it was better, but now I refuse to see the third one.\u000a\u000aI'd much rather Ralph Bakshi had finished it all, and done The Hobbit as well. I still watch his film, for all it's flaws, because it's far more loyal to the spirit of the thing.\u000a\u000aThe production was great. The wrapping was fantastic, but the present was a pair of socks.
